Properties.Name: input
Properties.Description: The input text to classify

Properties.Name: model
Properties.Description:
Two content moderations models are available: `text-moderation-stable` and
`text-moderation-latest`. The default is `text-moderation-latest` which will be automatically
upgraded over time. This ensures you are always using our most accurate model. If you use
`text-moderation-stable`, we will provide advanced notice before updating the model. Accuracy
of `text-moderation-stable` may be slightly lower than for `text-moderation-latest`.

Properties.Name: id
Properties.Description: The unique identifier for the moderation request.

Properties.Name: model
Properties.Description: The model used to generate the moderation results.

Properties.Name: results
Properties.Description: A list of moderation objects.

Properties.Name: flagged
Properties.Description: Whether the content violates [OpenAI's usage policies](/policies/usage-policies).

Properties.Name: categories
Properties.Description: A list of the categories, and whether they are flagged or not.

Properties.Name: hate
Properties.Description:
Content that expresses, incites, or promotes hate based on race, gender, ethnicity,
religion, nationality, sexual orientation, disability status, or caste. Hateful content
aimed at non-protected groups (e.g., chess players) is harrassment.

Properties.Name: hate/threatening
Properties.Description:
Hateful content that also includes violence or serious harm towards the targeted group
based on race, gender, ethnicity, religion, nationality, sexual orientation, disability
status, or caste.

Properties.Name: harassment
Properties.Description: Content that expresses, incites, or promotes harassing language towards any target.

Properties.Name: harassment/threatening
Properties.Description: Harassment content that also includes violence or serious harm towards any target.

Properties.Name: self-harm
Properties.Description:
Content that promotes, encourages, or depicts acts of self-harm, such as suicide, cutting,
and eating disorders.

Properties.Name: self-harm/intent
Properties.Description:
Content where the speaker expresses that they are engaging or intend to engage in acts of
self-harm, such as suicide, cutting, and eating disorders.

Properties.Name: self-harm/instructive
Properties.Description:
Content that encourages performing acts of self-harm, such as suicide, cutting, and eating
disorders, or that gives instructions or advice on how to commit such acts.

Properties.Name: sexual
Properties.Description:
Content meant to arouse sexual excitement, such as the description of sexual activity, or
that promotes sexual services (excluding sex education and wellness).

Properties.Name: sexual/minors
Properties.Description: Sexual content that includes an individual who is under 18 years old.

Properties.Name: violence
Properties.Description: Content that depicts death, violence, or physical injury.

Properties.Name: violence/graphic
Properties.Description: Content that depicts death, violence, or physical injury in graphic detail.

Properties.Name: category_scores
Properties.Description: A list of the categories along with their scores as predicted by model.

Properties.Description: The score for the category 'hate'.

Properties.Name: self-harm/instructive
Properties.Description: The score for the category 'self-harm/instructive'.

Properties.Name: sexual
Properties.Description: The score for the category 'sexual'.

Properties.Name: sexual/minors
Properties.Description: The score for the category 'sexual/minors'.

Properties.Name: violence
Properties.Description: The score for the category 'violence'.

Properties.Name: violence/graphic
Properties.Description: The score for the category 'violence/graphic'.

Properties.Name: b64_json

Properties.Name: prompt

Properties.Description:
The image to edit. Must be a valid PNG file, less than 4MB, and square. If mask is not
provided, image must have transparency, which will be used as the mask.

Properties.Name: mask
Properties.Description:
An additional image whose fully transparent areas (e.g. where alpha is zero) indicate where
`image` should be edited. Must be a valid PNG file, less than 4MB, and have the same dimensions
as `image`.

Properties.Name: n

The image to use as the basis for the variation(s). Must be a valid PNG file, less than 4MB,
and square.

ValueType.Name: Model
ValueType.Description: Describes an OpenAI model offering that can be used with the API.

Properties.Name: id
Properties.Description: The model identifier, which can be referenced in the API endpoints.

Properties.Name: object
Properties.Description: The object type, which is always "model".

Properties.Name: created
Properties.Description: The Unix timestamp (in seconds) when the model was created.

Properties.Name: owned_by
Properties.Description: The organization that owns the model.

Properties.Name: training_file
Properties.Description:
The ID of an uploaded file that contains training data.

See [upload file](/docs/api-reference/files/upload) for how to upload a file.

Your dataset must be formatted as a JSONL file, where each training example is a JSON object
with the keys "prompt" and "completion". Additionally, you must upload your file with the
purpose `fine-tune`.

See the [fine-tuning guide](/docs/guides/legacy-fine-tuning/creating-training-data) for more
details.

Properties.Name: validation_file
Properties.Description:
The ID of an uploaded file that contains validation data.

If you provide this file, the data is used to generate validation metrics periodically during
fine-tuning. These metrics can be viewed in the
[fine-tuning results file](/docs/guides/legacy-fine-tuning/analyzing-your-fine-tuned-model).
Your train and validation data should be mutually exclusive.

Your dataset must be formatted as a JSONL file, where each validation example is a JSON object
with the keys "prompt" and "completion". Additionally, you must upload your file with the
purpose `fine-tune`.

See the [fine-tuning guide](/docs/guides/legacy-fine-tuning/creating-training-data) for more
details.

Properties.Name: model
Properties.Description:
The name of the base model to fine-tune. You can select one of "ada", "babbage", "curie",
"davinci", or a fine-tuned model created after 2022-04-21 and before 2023-08-22. To learn more
about these models, see the [Models](/docs/models) documentation.

Properties.Name: n_epochs
Properties.Description:
The number of epochs to train the model for. An epoch refers to one full cycle through the
training dataset.

Properties.Name: batch_size
Properties.Description:
The batch size to use for training. The batch size is the number of training examples used to
train a single forward and backward pass.

By default, the batch size will be dynamically configured to be ~0.2% of the number of examples
in the training set, capped at 256 - in general, we've found that larger batch sizes tend to
work better for larger datasets.

Properties.Name: learning_rate_multiplier
Properties.Description:
The learning rate multiplier to use for training. The fine-tuning learning rate is the original
learning rate used for pretraining multiplied by this value.

By default, the learning rate multiplier is the 0.05, 0.1, or 0.2 depending on final
`batch_size` (larger learning rates tend to perform better with larger batch sizes). We
recommend experimenting with values in the range 0.02 to 0.2 to see what produces the best
results.

Properties.Name: prompt_loss_rate
Properties.Description:
The weight to use for loss on the prompt tokens. This controls how much the model tries to
learn to generate the prompt (as compared to the completion which always has a weight of 1.0),
and can add a stabilizing effect to training when completions are short.

If prompts are extremely long (relative to completions), it may make sense to reduce this
weight so as to avoid over-prioritizing learning the prompt.

Properties.Name: compute_classification_metrics
Properties.Description:
If set, we calculate classification-specific metrics such as accuracy and F-1 score using the
validation set at the end of every epoch. These metrics can be viewed in the
[results file](/docs/guides/legacy-fine-tuning/analyzing-your-fine-tuned-model).

In order to compute classification metrics, you must provide a `validation_file`. Additionally,
you must specify `classification_n_classes` for multiclass classification or
`classification_positive_class` for binary classification.

Properties.Name: classification_n_classes
Properties.Description:
The number of classes in a classification task.

This parameter is required for multiclass classification.

Properties.Name: classification_positive_class
Properties.Description:
The positive class in binary classification.

This parameter is needed to generate precision, recall, and F1 metrics when doing binary
classification.

Properties.Name: classification_betas
Properties.Description:
If this is provided, we calculate F-beta scores at the specified beta values. The F-beta score
is a generalization of F-1 score. This is only used for binary classification.

With a beta of 1 (i.e. the F-1 score), precision and recall are given the same weight. A larger
beta score puts more weight on recall and less on precision. A smaller beta score puts more
weight on precision and less on recall.

Properties.Name: suffix
Properties.Description:
A string of up to 18 characters that will be added to your fine-tuned model name.

For example, a `suffix` of "custom-model-name" would produce a model name like
`ada:ft-your-org:custom-model-name-2022-02-15-04-21-04`.

Properties.Name: hyperparams

The hyperparameters used for the fine-tuning job. See the
[fine-tuning guide](/docs/guides/legacy-fine-tuning/hyperparameters) for more details.

Properties.Name: n_epochs
Properties.Description:
The number of epochs to train the model for. An epoch refers to one full cycle through the
training dataset.

Properties.Name: batch_size

The batch size to use for training. The batch size is the number of training examples used to
train a single forward and backward pass.

Properties.Name: prompt_loss_weight

Properties.Name: learning_rate_multiplier

Properties.Name: training_files

ValueType.Name: OpenAIFile
ValueType.Description: The `File` object represents a document that has been uploaded to OpenAI.

Properties.Name: id
Properties.Description: The file identifier, which can be referenced in the API endpoints.

Properties.Name: object
Properties.Description: The object type, which is always "file".

Properties.Name: bytes

Properties.Name: createdAt

Properties.Name: filename

Properties.Name: purpose
Properties.Description: The intended purpose of the file. Currently, only "fine-tune" is supported.

Properties.Name: status
Properties.Description:
The current status of the file, which can be either `uploaded`, `processed`, `pending`,
`error`, `deleting` or `deleted`.

Properties.Name: status_details
Properties.Description:
Additional details about the status of the file. If the file is in the `error` state, this will
include a message describing the error.

Properties.Name: validation_files
Properties.Description: The list of files used for validation.

Properties.Name: result_files
Properties.Description: The compiled results files for the fine-tuning job.

Properties.Name: events
Properties.Description: The list of events that have been observed in the lifecycle of the FineTune job.

Properties.Name: file
Properties.Description:
Name of the [JSON Lines](https://jsonlines.readthedocs.io/en/latest/) file to be uploaded.

If the `purpose` is set to "fine-tune", the file will be used for fine-tuning.

Properties.Name: purpose
Properties.Description:
The intended purpose of the uploaded documents. Use "fine-tune" for
[fine-tuning](/docs/api-reference/fine-tuning). This allows us to validate the format of the
uploaded file.

Properties.Name: model
Properties.Description: ID of the model to use. You can use the [List models](/docs/api-reference/models/list) API to see all of your available models, or see our [Model overview](/docs/models/overview) for descriptions of them.

Properties.Name: input
Properties.Description:
Input text to embed, encoded as a string or array of tokens. To embed multiple inputs in a
single request, pass an array of strings or array of token arrays. Each input must not exceed
the max input tokens for the model (8191 tokens for `text-embedding-ada-002`) and cannot be an empty string.
[Example Python code](https://github.com/openai/openai-cookbook/blob/main/examples/How_to_count_tokens_with_tiktoken.ipynb)
for counting tokens.

Properties.Name: object
Properties.Description: The object type, which is always "embedding".

Properties.Name: model
Properties.Description: The name of the model used to generate the embedding.

Properties.Name: data
Properties.Description: The list of embeddings generated by the model.

ValueType.Name: Embedding
ValueType.Description: Represents an embedding vector returned by embedding endpoint.

Properties.Name: index
Properties.Description: The index of the embedding in the list of embeddings.

Properties.Name: object
Properties.Description: The object type, which is always "embedding".

Properties.Name: embedding
Properties.Description:
The embedding vector, which is a list of floats. The length of vector depends on the model as\
listed in the [embedding guide](/docs/guides/embeddings).

Properties.Name: usage
Properties.Description: The usage information for the request.

Properties.Name: prompt_tokens
Properties.Description: The number of tokens used by the prompt.

Properties.Name: total_tokens
Properties.Description: The total number of tokens used by the request.

Properties.Name: model
Properties.Description:
ID of the model to use. You can use the `text-davinci-edit-001` or `code-davinci-edit-001`
model with this endpoint.

Properties.Name: input
Properties.Description: The input text to use as a starting point for the edit.

Properties.Name: instruction
Properties.Description: The instruction that tells the model how to edit the prompt.

Properties.Name: n
Properties.Description: How many edits to generate for the input and instruction.

Properties.Name: temperature
Properties.Description:
What sampling temperature to use, between 0 and 2. Higher values like 0.8 will make the output
more random, while lower values like 0.2 will make it more focused and deterministic.

We generally recommend altering this or `top_p` but not both.

Properties.Name: top_p
Properties.Description:
An alternative to sampling with temperature, called nucleus sampling, where the model considers
the results of the tokens with top_p probability mass. So 0.1 means only the tokens comprising
the top 10% probability mass are considered.

We generally recommend altering this or `temperature` but not both.

Properties.Name: object
Properties.Description: The object type, which is always `edit`.

Properties.Name: created
Properties.Description: The Unix timestamp (in seconds) of when the edit was created.

Properties.Name: choices
Properties.Description: description: A list of edit choices. Can be more than one if `n` is greater than 1.

Properties.Name: text
Properties.Description: The edited result.

Properties.Name: index
Properties.Description: The index of the choice in the list of choices.

Properties.Name: finish_reason
Properties.Description:
The reason the model stopped generating tokens. This will be `stop` if the model hit a
natural stop point or a provided stop sequence, or `length` if the maximum number of tokens
specified in the request was reached.

Type.Name: CompletionUsage
Type.Description: Usage statistics for the completion request.

Properties.Name: prompt_tokens
Properties.Description: Number of tokens in the prompt.

Properties.Name: completion_tokens
Properties.Description: Number of tokens in the generated completion

Properties.Name: total_tokens
Properties.Description: Total number of tokens used in the request (prompt + completion).

Properties.Name: model
Properties.Description:
ID of the model to use. You can use the [List models](/docs/api-reference/models/list) API to
see all of your available models, or see our [Model overview](/docs/models/overview) for
descriptions of them.

Properties.Name: prompt
Properties.Description:
The prompt(s) to generate completions for, encoded as a string, array of strings, array of
tokens, or array of token arrays.

Note that <|endoftext|> is the document separator that the model sees during training, so if a
prompt is not specified the model will generate as if from the beginning of a new document.

Properties.Name: suffix
Properties.Description: The suffix that comes after a completion of inserted text.

Properties.Name: temperature
Properties.Description:
What sampling temperature to use, between 0 and 2. Higher values like 0.8 will make the output
more random, while lower values like 0.2 will make it more focused and deterministic.

We generally recommend altering this or `top_p` but not both.

Properties.Name: top_p
Properties.Description:
An alternative to sampling with temperature, called nucleus sampling, where the model considers
the results of the tokens with top_p probability mass. So 0.1 means only the tokens comprising
the top 10% probability mass are considered.

We generally recommend altering this or `temperature` but not both.

Properties.Name: n
Properties.Description:
How many completions to generate for each prompt.
**Note:** Because this parameter generates many completions, it can quickly consume your token
quota. Use carefully and ensure that you have reasonable settings for `max_tokens` and `stop`.

Properties.Name: max_tokens
Properties.Description:
The maximum number of [tokens](/tokenizer) to generate in the completion.

The token count of your prompt plus `max_tokens` cannot exceed the model's context length.
[Example Python code](https://github.com/openai/openai-cookbook/blob/main/examples/How_to_count_tokens_with_tiktoken.ipynb)
for counting tokens.

Properties.Name: stop
Properties.Description: Up to 4 sequences where the API will stop generating further tokens.

Properties.Name: presence_penalty
Properties.Description:
Number between -2.0 and 2.0. Positive values penalize new tokens based on whether they appear
in the text so far, increasing the model's likelihood to talk about new topics.

[See more information about frequency and presence penalties.](/docs/guides/gpt/parameter-details)

Properties.Name: frequency_penalty
Properties.Description:
Number between -2.0 and 2.0. Positive values penalize new tokens based on their existing
frequency in the text so far, decreasing the model's likelihood to repeat the same line
verbatim.

[See more information about frequency and presence penalties.](/docs/guides/gpt/parameter-details)

Properties.Name: logit_bias
Properties.Description:
Modify the likelihood of specified tokens appearing in the completion.
Accepts a json object that maps tokens (specified by their token ID in the tokenizer) to an
associated bias value from -100 to 100. Mathematically, the bias is added to the logits
generated by the model prior to sampling. The exact effect will vary per model, but values
between -1 and 1 should decrease or increase likelihood of selection; values like -100 or 100
should result in a ban or exclusive selection of the relevant token.

Properties.Name: user
Properties.Description:
A unique identifier representing your end-user, which can help OpenAI to monitor and detect
abuse. [Learn more](/docs/guides/safety-best-practices/end-user-ids).

Properties.Name: stream
Properties.Description:
If set, partial message deltas will be sent, like in ChatGPT. Tokens will be sent as data-only
[server-sent events](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Server-sent_events/Using_server-sent_events#Event_stream_format)
as they become available, with the stream terminated by a `data: [DONE]` message.
[Example Python code](https://github.com/openai/openai-cookbook/blob/main/examples/How_to_stream_completions.ipynb).

Properties.Name: logprobs
Properties.Description:
Include the log probabilities on the `logprobs` most likely tokens, as well the chosen tokens.
For example, if `logprobs` is 5, the API will return a list of the 5 most likely tokens. The
API will always return the `logprob` of the sampled token, so there may be up to `logprobs+1`
elements in the response.

The maximum value for `logprobs` is 5.

Properties.Name: echo
Properties.Description: Echo back the prompt in addition to the completion

Properties.Name: best_of
Properties.Description:
Generates `best_of` completions server-side and returns the "best" (the one with the highest
log probability per token). Results cannot be streamed.

When used with `n`, `best_of` controls the number of candidate completions and `n` specifies
how many to return  `best_of` must be greater than `n`.

**Note:** Because this parameter generates many completions, it can quickly consume your token
quota. Use carefully and ensure that you have reasonable settings for `max_tokens` and `stop`.

Models.Name: CreateCompletionResponse
Models.Description:
Represents a completion response from the API. Note: both the streamed and non-streamed response
objects share the same shape (unlike the chat endpoint).

Properties.Name: id
Properties.Description: A unique identifier for the completion.

Properties.Name: object
Properties.Description: The object type, which is always `text_completion`.

Properties.Name: created
Properties.Description: The Unix timestamp (in seconds) of when the completion was created.

Properties.Name: model
Properties.Description: The model used for the completion.

Properties.Name: choices
Properties.Description: The list of completion choices the model generated for the input.

Properties.Name: finish_reason
Properties.Description:
The reason the model stopped generating tokens. This will be `stop` if the model hit a
natural stop point or a provided stop sequence, or `content_filter` if content was omitted
due to a flag from our content filters, `length` if the maximum number of tokens specified
in the request was reached, or `content_filter` if content was omitted due to a flag from our
content filters.

Properties.Name: training_file
Properties.Description:
The ID of an uploaded file that contains training data.

See [upload file](/docs/api-reference/files/upload) for how to upload a file.

Your dataset must be formatted as a JSONL file. Additionally, you must upload your file with
the purpose `fine-tune`.

See the [fine-tuning guide](/docs/guides/fine-tuning) for more details.

Properties.Name: validation_file
Properties.Description:
The ID of an uploaded file that contains validation data.

If you provide this file, the data is used to generate validation metrics periodically during
fine-tuning. These metrics can be viewed in the fine-tuning results file. The same data should
not be present in both train and validation files.

Your dataset must be formatted as a JSONL file. You must upload your file with the purpose
`fine-tune`.

See the [fine-tuning guide](/docs/guides/fine-tuning) for more details.

Properties.Name: model
Properties.Description:
The name of the model to fine-tune. You can select one of the
[supported models](/docs/guides/fine-tuning/what-models-can-be-fine-tuned).

Properties.Name: hyperparameters
Properties.Description: The hyperparameters used for the fine-tuning job.

Properties.Name: n_epochs
Properties.Description:
The number of epochs to train the model for. An epoch refers to one full cycle through the
training dataset.

Properties.Name: suffix
Properties.Description:
A string of up to 18 characters that will be added to your fine-tuned model name.

For example, a `suffix` of "custom-model-name" would produce a model name like
`ft:gpt-3.5-turbo:openai:custom-model-name:7p4lURel`.

Properties.Name: id
Properties.Description: The object identifier, which can be referenced in the API endpoints.

Properties.Name: object
Properties.Description: The object type, which is always "fine_tuning.job".

Properties.Name: created_at
Properties.Description: The Unix timestamp (in seconds) for when the fine-tuning job was created.

Properties.Name: finished_at
Properties.Description:
The Unix timestamp (in seconds) for when the fine-tuning job was finished. The value will be
null if the fine-tuning job is still running.

Properties.Name: model
Properties.Description: The base model that is being fine-tuned.

Properties.Name: fine_tuned_model
Properties.Description:
The name of the fine-tuned model that is being created. The value will be null if the
fine-tuning job is still running.

Properties.Name: organization_id
Properties.Description: The organization that owns the fine-tuning job.

Properties.Name: status
Properties.Description:
The current status of the fine-tuning job, which can be either `created`, `pending`, `running`,
`succeeded`, `failed`, or `cancelled`.

Properties.Name: hyperparameters
Properties.Description:
The hyperparameters used for the fine-tuning job. See the
[fine-tuning guide](/docs/guides/fine-tuning) for more details.

Properties.Name: n_epochs
Properties.Description:
The number of epochs to train the model for. An epoch refers to one full cycle through the
training dataset.

"Auto" decides the optimal number of epochs based on the size of the dataset. If setting the
number manually, we support any number between 1 and 50 epochs.

Properties.Name: training_file
Properties.Description:
The file ID used for training. You can retrieve the training data with the
[Files API](/docs/api-reference/files/retrieve-contents).

Properties.Name: validation_file
Properties.Description:
The file ID used for validation. You can retrieve the validation results with the
[Files API](/docs/api-reference/files/retrieve-contents).

Properties.Name: result_files
Properties.Description:
The compiled results file ID(s) for the fine-tuning job. You can retrieve the results with the
[Files API](/docs/api-reference/files/retrieve-contents).

Properties.Name: trained_tokens
Properties.Description:
The total number of billable tokens processed by this fine tuning job. The value will be null
if the fine-tuning job is still running.

Properties.Name: error
Properties.Description:
For fine-tuning jobs that have `failed`, this will contain more information on the cause of the
failure.

Properties.Name: message
Properties.Description: A human-readable error message.

Properties.Name: code
Properties.Description: A machine-readable error code.

Properties.Name: param
Properties.Description:
The parameter that was invalid, usually `training_file` or `validation_file`. This field
will be null if the failure was not parameter-specific.

Properties.Name: role
Properties.Description: The role of the messages author. One of `system`, `user`, `assistant`, or `function`.

Properties.Name: content
Properties.Description:
The contents of the message. `content` is required for all messages, and may be null for
assistant messages with function calls.

Properties.Name: name
Properties.Description:
The name of the author of this message. `name` is required if role is `function`, and it
should be the name of the function whose response is in the `content`. May contain a-z,
A-Z, 0-9, and underscores, with a maximum length of 64 characters.

Properties.Name: function_call
Properties.Description: The name and arguments of a function that should be called, as generated by the model.

Properties.Name: name
Properties.Description: The name of the function to call.

Properties.Name: arguments
Properties.Description:
The arguments to call the function with, as generated by the model in JSON format. Note that
the model does not always generate valid JSON, and may hallucinate parameters not defined by
your function schema. Validate the arguments in your code before calling your function.

Properties.Name: name
Properties.Description:
The name of the function to be called. Must be a-z, A-Z, 0-9, or contain underscores and
dashes, with a maximum length of 64.

Properties.Name: description
Properties.Description:
A description of what the function does, used by the model to choose when and how to call the
function.

Properties.Name: parameters
Properties.Description:
The parameters the functions accepts, described as a JSON Schema object. See the
[guide](/docs/guides/gpt/function-calling) for examples, and the
[JSON Schema reference](https://json-schema.org/understanding-json-schema/) for documentation
about the format.\n\nTo describe a function that accepts no parameters, provide the value
`{\"type\": \"object\", \"properties\": {}}`.

Properties.Name: name
Properties.Description: The name of the function to call.

Models.Name: CreateChatCompletionResponse
Models.Description: Represents a chat completion response returned by model, based on the provided input.

Properties.Name: id
Properties.Description: A unique identifier for the chat completion.

Properties.Name: object
Properties.Description: The object type, which is always `chat.completion`.

Properties.Name: created
Properties.Description: The Unix timestamp (in seconds) of when the chat completion was created.

Properties.Name: model
Properties.Description: The model used for the chat completion.

Properties.Name: choices
Properties.Description: A list of chat completion choices. Can be more than one if `n` is greater than 1.

Properties.Name: index
Properties.Description: The index of the choice in the list of choices.

Properties.Name: role
Properties.Description: The role of the author of this message.

Properties.Name: content
Properties.Description: The contents of the message.

Properties.Name: function_call
Properties.Description: The name and arguments of a function that should be called, as generated by the model.

Properties.Name: name
Properties.Description: The name of the function to call.

Properties.Name: arguments
Properties.Description:
The arguments to call the function with, as generated by the model in JSON format. Note that
the model does not always generate valid JSON, and may hallucinate parameters not defined by
your function schema. Validate the arguments in your code before calling your function.

Properties.Name: finish_reason
Properties.Description:
The reason the model stopped generating tokens. This will be `stop` if the model hit a
natural stop point or a provided stop sequence, `length` if the maximum number of tokens
specified in the request was reached, `content_filter` if the content was omitted due to
a flag from our content filters, or `function_call` if the model called a function.

Properties.Name: file
Properties.Description:
The audio file object (not file name) to translate, in one of these formats: flac, mp3, mp4,
mpeg, mpga, m4a, ogg, wav, or webm.

Properties.Name: model
Properties.Description: ID of the model to use. Only `whisper-1` is currently available.

Properties.Name: prompt
Properties.Description:
An optional text to guide the model's style or continue a previous audio segment. The
[prompt](/docs/guides/speech-to-text/prompting) should match the audio language.

Properties.Name: response_format
Properties.Description:
The format of the transcript output, in one of these options: json, text, srt, verbose_json, or
vtt.

Properties.Name: temperature
Properties.Description:
The sampling temperature, between 0 and 1. Higher values like 0.8 will make the output more
random, while lower values like 0.2 will make it more focused and deterministic. If set to 0,
the model will use [log probability](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Log_probability) to
automatically increase the temperature until certain thresholds are hit.

Properties.Name: file
Properties.Description:
The audio file object (not file name) to transcribe, in one of these formats: flac, mp3, mp4,
mpeg, mpga, m4a, ogg, wav, or webm.

Properties.Name: model
Properties.Description: ID of the model to use. Only `whisper-1` is currently available.

Properties.Name: prompt
Properties.Description:
An optional text to guide the model's style or continue a previous audio segment. The
[prompt](/docs/guides/speech-to-text/prompting) should match the audio language.

Properties.Name: response_format
Properties.Description:
The format of the transcript output, in one of these options: json, text, srt, verbose_json, or
vtt.

Properties.Name: temperature
Properties.Description:
The sampling temperature, between 0 and 1. Higher values like 0.8 will make the output more
random, while lower values like 0.2 will make it more focused and deterministic. If set to 0,
the model will use [log probability](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Log_probability) to
automatically increase the temperature until certain thresholds are hit.

Properties.Name: language
Properties.Description:
The language of the input audio. Supplying the input language in
[ISO-639-1](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_ISO_639-1_codes) format will improve accuracy
and latency.

Properties.Name: model
Properties.Description:
ID of the model to use. See the [model endpoint compatibility](/docs/models/model-endpoint-compatibility)
table for details on which models work with the Chat API.

Properties.Name: messages
Properties.Description:
A list of messages comprising the conversation so far.
[Example Python code](https://github.com/openai/openai-cookbook/blob/main/examples/How_to_format_inputs_to_ChatGPT_models.ipynb).

Properties.Name: functions
Properties.Description: A list of functions the model may generate JSON inputs for.

Properties.Name: function_call
Properties.Description:
Controls how the model responds to function calls. `none` means the model does not call a
function, and responds to the end-user. `auto` means the model can pick between an end-user or
calling a function.  Specifying a particular function via `{\"name":\ \"my_function\"}` forces the
model to call that function. `none` is the default when no functions are present. `auto` is the
default if functions are present.

Properties.Name: temperature
Properties.Description:
What sampling temperature to use, between 0 and 2. Higher values like 0.8 will make the output
more random, while lower values like 0.2 will make it more focused and deterministic.

We generally recommend altering this or `top_p` but not both.

Properties.Name: top_p
Properties.Description:
An alternative to sampling with temperature, called nucleus sampling, where the model considers
the results of the tokens with top_p probability mass. So 0.1 means only the tokens comprising
the top 10% probability mass are considered.

We generally recommend altering this or `temperature` but not both.

Properties.Name: n
Properties.Description:
How many completions to generate for each prompt.
**Note:** Because this parameter generates many completions, it can quickly consume your token
quota. Use carefully and ensure that you have reasonable settings for `max_tokens` and `stop`.

Properties.Name: max_tokens
Properties.Description:
The maximum number of [tokens](/tokenizer) to generate in the completion.

The token count of your prompt plus `max_tokens` cannot exceed the model's context length.
[Example Python code](https://github.com/openai/openai-cookbook/blob/main/examples/How_to_count_tokens_with_tiktoken.ipynb)
for counting tokens.

Properties.Name: stop
Properties.Description: Up to 4 sequences where the API will stop generating further tokens.

Properties.Name: presence_penalty
Properties.Description:
Number between -2.0 and 2.0. Positive values penalize new tokens based on whether they appear
in the text so far, increasing the model's likelihood to talk about new topics.

[See more information about frequency and presence penalties.](/docs/guides/gpt/parameter-details)

Properties.Name: frequency_penalty
Properties.Description:
Number between -2.0 and 2.0. Positive values penalize new tokens based on their existing
frequency in the text so far, decreasing the model's likelihood to repeat the same line
verbatim.

[See more information about frequency and presence penalties.](/docs/guides/gpt/parameter-details)

Properties.Name: logit_bias
Properties.Description:
Modify the likelihood of specified tokens appearing in the completion.
Accepts a json object that maps tokens (specified by their token ID in the tokenizer) to an
associated bias value from -100 to 100. Mathematically, the bias is added to the logits
generated by the model prior to sampling. The exact effect will vary per model, but values
between -1 and 1 should decrease or increase likelihood of selection; values like -100 or 100
should result in a ban or exclusive selection of the relevant token.

Properties.Name: user
Properties.Description:
A unique identifier representing your end-user, which can help OpenAI to monitor and detect
abuse. [Learn more](/docs/guides/safety-best-practices/end-user-ids).

Properties.Name: stream
Properties.Description:
If set, partial message deltas will be sent, like in ChatGPT. Tokens will be sent as data-only
[server-sent events](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Server-sent_events/Using_server-sent_events#Event_stream_format)
as they become available, with the stream terminated by a `data: [DONE]` message.
[Example Python code](https://github.com/openai/openai-cookbook/blob/main/examples/How_to_stream_completions.ipynb).
